\section*{Solution}

The energy \(E\) transferred in an electric field is given by the equation:
\[
E = V \cdot Q
\]
where \(E\) is the energy, \(V\) is the potential difference, and \(Q\) is the charge transferred.

Given:
\[
E = 10^{-5} \, \text{J}, \quad V = 5 \times 10^6 \, \text{V}
\]

We can solve for \(Q\) as follows:
\[
Q = \frac{E}{V} = \frac{10^{-5} \, \text{J}}{5 \times 10^6 \, \text{V}} = 2 \times 10^{-12} \, \text{C}
\]

Next, to find the number of electrons \(n\) that have flowed, we use the charge of a single electron \(e = 1.6 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{C}\):
\[
n = \frac{Q}{e} = \frac{2 \times 10^{-12} \, \text{C}}{1.6 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{C/electron}} \approx 1.25 \times 10^7 \, \text{electrons}
\]

Thus, the charge transferred is \(2 \times 10^{-12} \, \text{C}\) and approximately \(1.25 \times 10^7\) electrons have flowed.

